         <desc type="abstract" xml:id="abstractx9999-1">and <quote>
               <placeName>Caesarea</placeName>
            </quote> is directly attested at <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/95147024"
               role="author">Jerome</persName>, <title xml:lang="en" ref="" type="uniform" level="m"
               >Book of Places</title>
            <ref target="#bibx9999-1">137</ref>. This passage was written circa <origDate
               notBefore="0390" notAfter="420"
               period="#byzantine #earlyIslamic #crusader #lateIslamic #ottoman #britishTerritorialAdministration #britishMandate"
               >390-420 CE</origDate> possibly in <origPlace
               ref="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/687856">Bethlehem</origPlace>.</desc>
         <desc type="context">In his lexicon of place names in Hebrew Scripture, Jerome wrote that
            Nafeddor named at <title>Joshua 11:12</title> was located near Caesarea Maritima on the
            road to Ptolemais (Akko), repeating his lemma under Dor Nafeth (79). He also cited the
            Greek translation of Hebrew Scripture by Symmachus in the late 2nd century C.E. The same
            information is recorded in the parallel passage at <title>Eusebius, Dictionary of Place
               Names 136</title>, written roughly one century before Jerome‚Äôs work.</desc>
         <ab type="edition" xml:lang="la" xml:id="quotex9999-1" source="#bibx9999-1">
            <anchor xml:id="testimonia-x9999.la.1" corresp="#testimonia-x9999.en.1"/>
            <note type="textual">Nefeddor, quod Symmachus interpretatur Maritimam. Dor autem est
               oppidum iam desertum in nono miliario <placeName>Caesareae</placeName> pergentibus
               Ptoloma√Ødem.</note>
            <note type="textual">Ed. Klosterman 1904</note>
            <idno type="CTS-URN"/>
            <ref target=""/>
         </ab>
         <ab type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:id="quotex9999-2" source="#bibx9999-2">
            <anchor xml:id="testimonia-x9999.en.1" corresp="#testimonia-x9999.la.1"/>Nefeddor, which
            Symmachus translates Maritima. Dor is a city now deserted at milestone 9 for those
            travelling from <placeName>Caesarea</placeName> to Ptolema√Øs.<note type="translation"
               >Trans. J. L. Rife</note>
            <idno type="CTS-URN"/>
            <ref target=""/>
         </ab>
